prior_attempts.prompt_text:
Decompose the problem into a few genuinely useful subproblems that expose the key mathematical checks needed for the final answer.

Return exactly one JSON object in this format:
{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "optional string",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "plain-text subproblem for the first helper"
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "how the parent should combine the child results"
}

Decompose the problem into helper tasks that directly test small answer possibilities, rule out impossible cases, and compute the first viable case. Make each helper responsible for one concrete mathematical check.

Return exactly one JSON object in this format:
{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "optional string",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "plain-text subproblem for the first helper"
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "how the parent should combine the child results"
}

Decompose the problem into a maximum of two highly focused subproblems for other agents. Each helper should be assigned a single, atomic task that contributes to the final solution. Do not restate the original question. Do not hardcode the number of helpers, but ensure the total count never exceeds two.

Use plain text only inside helper instructions. Do not use markdown, code fences, or LaTeX-style backslashes.

Return exactly one JSON object in this format:
{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "optional string",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "plain-text subproblem for the first helper"
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "how the parent should combine the child results"
}

